{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17609"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17609"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.09,0.46,0.23,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78220"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63629"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6660"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78220"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal carotid artery follows a complex course through four segments as it travels from the neck to the brain, giving off several important branches along its path.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first branch of the internal carotid artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior choroidal artery","Middle meningeal artery","Ophthalmic artery","Posterior communicating artery","Superior hypophyseal artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eophthalmic artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the first branch of the internal carotid artery, arising from the cerebral (supraclinoid) segment after the vessel exits the cavernous sinus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior choroidal artery\u003C/strong\u003E - This arises after the ophthalmic and posterior communicating arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle meningeal artery\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a branch of the maxillary artery, not the internal carotid artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior communicating artery\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the second major branch of the cerebral segment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior hypophyseal artery\u003C/strong\u003E - These are small branches from the cavernous segment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter giving off the ophthalmic artery, the internal carotid artery continues to give rise to the posterior communicating artery and anterior choroidal artery before terminating as the anterior and middle cerebral arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The internal carotid artery has four main segments: cervical, petrous, cavernous, and cerebral.","The ophthalmic artery is the first branch of the cerebral segment of the internal carotid artery.","After the ophthalmic artery, the internal carotid artery gives off the posterior communicating and anterior choroidal arteries before its terminal bifurcation."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cInternal Carotid Artery\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is und